COMMENTS TO AUTHOR:\
\
Reviewer #1: This manuscript provides a description of a monolithically fabricated ion trap suitable for experiments with two-dimensional ion crystals, together with first experiments coupling to vibrational sidebands of two-dimensional ion crystals.\
Quantum information processing with 2D ion crystals instead of linear strings of arrays is of interest from the point of view of (1) increasing the number of qubits that can be coupled, and (2) realizing an ion-qubit geometry for analog quantum simulations that enable the study of 2d lattice systems. So far, the only spin-spin simulations undertaken with ions in a 2d geometry have been performed in Penning traps where the rotation of planar crystals makes single-qubit manipulation and state detection quite challenging.\
\
Wang and colleagues present the design and fabrication in sufficient detail and report on experiments that open the prospect of carrying out spin-spin simulations with tens of ions. I recommend publication of the manuscript based on the novelty of the results, but would like to ask the authors to answer the following questions:\
\
1. In section 3, it is stated that adjustment of two voltages, V_C and V_\{NC\}, enables the rotation of the principal axes of the pseudopotential resulting from the overall potential given in equation (1), which, in addition, features the rf-voltage as a third control parameter. Shouldn't one want to have four control parameters if one wishes to set the three oscillation frequencies of an ion and to control in addition the orientation of the principal axes in a plane?  \
\
2. Fig. 1a shows a U-shaped rf-rail. Is this rf-electrode just from one side, and if so, are there any problems expected from rf-currents flowing in opposite directions that might give rise to rf-induced ac-Zeeman shifts? Is the resistivity of the electrode small enough so that the one can expect the voltages on opposite rf-electrodes to be equal?\
\
3.I did not understand the meaning of equation (3) and the statement that "\\delta z is related to the size of the crystal". I understand that the first derivative of the potential with respect to y has to vanish, but what does it mean that it should vanish in (x,z) = (0,\\delta y)? Why not just in (x,z)=(0,0), or if one wishes make it vanish in an extended region along z, why isn't there a similar condition for the x-direction?\
\
4. Section 3: the authors state a mean phonon number after Doppler cooling, but do not mention the vibrational frequency for which this number was found. To put it into a context, it would be important to know the trap frequency.\
\
5. Section 3: the statement that Raman beams "are applied perpendicular to the z-axis" should be made more precise by stating the plane to which the Raman k-vector is normal.\
\
6. Section 4: the sentence "\'a1\'adthese frequencies look violating the bound for the 2D crystal in Fig. 2e. However, it is a complicated situation" should be rephrased and better explained. Simply referring to appendix E at this point is frustrating to the reader.\
\
7. Figure 5: it would be nice if a slightly more detailed explanation of the effect of off-resonant coupling to the other two out-of-plane modes could be given (for example, I immediately wondered how close the other non-center-of-mass mode is in frequency space to the driven mode. Is the thermal occupation of these modes a problem, etc.)\
\
