Reviewer #2: The central question addressed by the manuscript is important. What are the conditions to use self-assembled planar ion crystals for quantum simulation? Can you address vibrational modes as for the case of a linear ion crystal? Therefore, I am in principle very positive about the topic and that experimental work is done in this field.  However, this manuscript does not answer the questions sufficiently. The three-ion data and simulations are a fully distinct topic and the authors did not manage to merge or even connect this part in a good way with the other.  I would advise them to concentrate on either one of the parts\
In detail: The abstract is rather an introduction. The authors should cut the beginning, cut all the general facts and describe what has been done here. One sentence of gerenal intro may stay, but not more. On the other hand, there is not a single experimental fact except the rather unimportant spacing of the ions. What means "several dozens", or "carful design", what means "large optical access"? Better make this specific and give relevant numbers. What is really the core message of this work? \
The introduction contains relevant literature, but I would ask the authors to use citesort such that it converts in line 48 to [1-17]. Also, this way of citing seems to me a bit uncharitable, to collect basically all the references in one bracket and not to be specific a little more about them. In the later sections, one can barely find references, which is strange. This should be changed. \
Line 32 there is something wrong with the reference [?,36].\
Line 61 ff, I do not see any reference to calculations of mode frequencies which take the micromotion into account. \
